      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my earth science midterm and im a bit confused about cold fronts. can u explain how they actually form and what kind of weather we usually see right after one moves through? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, I'd be happy to help you with that! Cold fronts are formed when a cold air mass moves into an area occupied by warmer air. The cold air, being denser, slides underneath the warmer air, pushing it upward. This upward movement of warm air causes it to cool and condense, forming clouds and often leading to precipitation. So, when a cold front moves through, you can expect a sudden drop in temperature, often accompanied by thunderstorms, heavy rain, or even snow, depending on the season and location. It's like a big, chilly, and sometimes stormy wave of cold air that sweeps through the warmer air, causing all sorts of weather changes. Keep studying, and you'll be ready for your midterm! Good luck!",
